{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520275"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:21:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:21:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13171"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13171"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.39,0.02,0.19,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103676"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103676"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 62-year-old woman presents with a two month history of anorexia and weight loss. An endoscopy is performed and she is found to have a carcinoma of the proximal stomach.\u00a0A CT scan is performed as part of the staging of the tumour (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is evident on the CT scan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid cyst","Metastatic deposit in the liver","Adrenal adenoma","Gallstone","Renal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith the increasing use of sophisticated imaging, incidental findings are an important dynamic in today\u0027s medical practice. Recognising them as such and providing appropriate advice to the patient can be challenging. This CT scan shows a \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstone\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). The gallstone has an outer ring of calcification. This is an incidental finding. Gallstones stones are very common and it is estimated that some 30% of the population will develop gallstones over their lifetime. In most cases these stones will remain asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith the sophistication of today\u0027s imaging technology and the frequency of its use, incidental findings are being picked up with increasing frequency. In one study of trauma patients undergoing various forms of CT imaging, incidental findings were found in 40% of cases. These can include gallstones, adrenal adenomas, pulmonary nodules and renal cysts. Similar frequencies have been reported in non-trauma settings. One of the dilemmas posed by these findings is the need to pass on the information to the patients and the unnecessary anxiety that might be caused. In the large majority of cases these findings have no immediate clinical significance. Less than 2% of these incidental findings have serious implications - such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic deposits\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease is now very uncommon in Australia, but \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are found occasionally as incidental findings - particularly in individuals who have originated from sheep farming areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E are relatively common \u0027incidentalomas,\u0027 and it is estimated that 10% of individuals over the age of 70 years will have such a lesion. In the large majority of cases these adenomas with be of no clinical significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreasingly, \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are now being found incidentally during an imaging study and it is estimated that some 30% of renal cell carcinomas are diagnosed in this manner, rather than with the typical symptoms of haematuria, loin pain or weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstones are common incidental findings on imaging studies."],"references":["Ibrahim M, Sarvepalle S, Morris-Stiff G, et al. Gallstones: Watch and wait, or intervene? Clev Cli J Med. 2018; 85:323-31.","Andrawes P, Picon AI, Shariff MA, et al. CT scan incidental findings in trauma patients: does it impact hospital length of\u00a0stay? Trauma Surg Acute Care Open 2017;2:1\u20136"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13171"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20292"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20293"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20292"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/m1IDViokz58ZfQXbXhRaWr2fGQM2CE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/m1IDViokz58ZfQXbXhRaWr2fGQM2CE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":413}},{"type":"media","id":"20293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20293"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c8uKGWs9vz2BAPCnYOZVCKCeVpnRY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c8uKGWs9vz2BAPCnYOZVCKCeVpnRY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":413}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86093"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T16:21:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T16:22:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5608"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103676"}}}